{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504187"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:12:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:12:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2307"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2307"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.39,0.28,0.07,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2307"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78315"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2307"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2307"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63695"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1287"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1313"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23642"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78315"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 87-year-old woman from a nursing home presents to the Emergency Department with a seven hour history of sudden onset left-sided weakness. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus (on metformin and empagliflozin), congestive heart failure (on bisoprolol, furosemide, and spironolactone) and hypertension (on ramipril).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her blood pressure is 185/95 mmHg, pulse 100/min, temperature 37.2\u2103, respiratory rate 16/min and oxygen saturation is 94% on room air. She has right basal crackles on lung auscultation. Her neurological examination demonstrates left lower facial, arm and leg weakness. She has left-sided visual neglect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer blood glucose level is 15 mmol/L. A CT head demonstrates an established area of infarction within the right middle cerebral artery territory and no haemorrhage. There is no large vessel occlusion on CT angiography.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral statin therapy","Oral antiplatelet therapy","Intravenous anti-hypertensive","High-flow oxygen","Intravenous thrombolysis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has had an ischaemic stroke. Given she is outside of the conventional time window for thrombolysis with established infarction and there is no proximal large vessel occlusion that would be amenable to endovascular clot retrieval, the most appropriate management would be \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eantiplatelet therapy\u003C/strong\u003E. This may be aspirin monotherapy or aspirin and clopidogrel, depending on the volume of dead brain and her anticipated bleeding risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral statin therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for secondary prevention of ischaemic stroke but has no established benefit in the acute setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous anti-hypertensive\u003C/strong\u003E is not required. Permissive hypertension up to 220/120 mmHg is acceptable in acute ischaemic stroke since cerebral perfusion is dependent on mean arterial pressure. Her current blood pressure of 185/95 mmHg is within acceptable limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-flow oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E should only be used in hypoxic stroke patients to achieve a target saturation of 94-98%. High concentrations of oxygen should be avoided unless oxygen saturations are \u0026lt;94%, as high oxygen concentrations may increase reactive oxygen species, increasing cerebral tissue damage. Her current saturation of 94% is adequate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous thrombolysis\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated in this case as the patient is outside the therapeutic window (\u0026gt;4.5 hours) and already has established infarction on CT. Thrombolysis in this setting would increase the risk of haemorrhagic transformation without providing benefit.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Antiplatelet therapy should be started promptly in patients who have had an ischaemic stroke.","Permissive hypertension up to 220/120 mmHg is acceptable in acute ischaemic stroke.","Supplemental oxygen is only indicated if saturations are below 94% in acute stroke."],"references":["Kernan WN, Ovbiagele B, Black HR, Bravata DM, Chimowitz MI, Ezekowitz MD, et al; American Heart Association Stroke Council, Council on Cardiovascular and Stroke Nursing, Council on Clinical Cardiology, and Council on Peripheral Vascular Disease. Guidelines for the prevention of stroke in patients with stroke and transient ischemic attack: a guideline for healthcare professionals from the American Heart Association/American Stroke Association. Stroke. 2014 Jul;45(7):2160-236. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24788967/","Sandercock P, Gubitz G, Foley P, Counsell C. Antiplatelet therapy for acute ischaemic stroke. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2003;(2):CD000029. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD000029. Update in: Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2008 Jul 16;(3):CD000029. Available at: https://www.cochrane.org/CD000029/STROKE_oral-antiplatelet-therapy-acute-ischaemic-stroke","The International Stroke Trial (IST): a randomised trial of aspirin, subcutaneous heparin, both, or neither among 19435 patients with acute ischaemic stroke. International Stroke Trial Collaborative Group. Lancet. 1997 May 31;349(9065):1569-81. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9174558/","Chen ZM, Sandercock P, Pan HC, Counsell C, Collins R, Liu LS, et al.. Indications for early aspirin use in acute ischemic stroke: a combined analysis of 40 000 randomized patients from the Chinese acute stroke trial and the international stroke trial. On behalf of the CAST and IST collaborative groups. Stroke. 2000; 31:1240\u20131249. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10835439/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63695"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2307"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63695"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T12:46:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T12:46:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2307"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78315"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/ap